November 13, 1997<br><br>
Vietnam Stops To Mourn Typhoon Dead<br><br>
Filed at 1:14 p.m. EST<br><br>
By The Associated Press<br>
HANOI, Vietnam (AP) -- Vietnam's top leaders observed a moment of silence Thursday for the hundreds of people killed by Typhoon Linda and thousands more who are still missing. <br><br>
During a brief ceremony at the national legislature, the country's troika leadership -- Premier Phan Van Khai, President Tran Duc Luong and Communist Party chief Do Muoi -- bowed their heads in respect for the dead. <br><br>
Typhoon Linda wrecked havoc on southern Vietnam's Ca Mau and Kien Giang provinces two weeks ago, killing at least 435 people and destroying entire villages. At least 3,406 people -- many of them fishermen -- are still missing after the worst typhoon to hit southern Vietnam since 1904. <br><br>
The United States, Canada, France and China are among those offering relief aid to the victims. <br><br>
The search for the missing fishermen was continuing, but officials said it was very unlikely that any more survivors would be found. <br><br>

